<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<subsection xml:id="ss-recursive-probability"><title>Recursion in Probability</title>

<p>Recursion can frequently be used to simplify computations relating to random variables. We illustrate this with an example.</p>

<example><title>Waiting for a Six</title> 
<p>Consider a simple game in which the outcome involves rolling a standard, fair six-side die until a 6 is rolled. For any positive integer <m>k</m> isn't too difficult to compute the probability that exactly <m>k</m> rolls are needed to see a 6.  Rolls of a die are independent and each roll is a <xref ref="def-binomial-trial" text="title"/>.  If we view rolling a 6 as success the probability that we have <m>k-1</m> failures followed by a success is <m>p(k)=\frac{5}{6}^{k-1}\cdot \frac{1}{6}</m>. If we define the random variable <m>K</m> to be the number rolls need to get a 6, then the expected values of <m>K</m> is 
<me> E(K)=\sum{k=1}^{\infty} k p(k)= \sum{k=1}^{\infty} k \frac{5}{6}^{k-1}\cdot \frac{1}{6}</me>
This expression for <m>E(K)</m> can be simplified in several ways, but probably the simplest is to observe that whatever the expected value of <m>K</m> is, if you roll the die and don't get a 6 the expected additional rolls to get a 6 is still <m>E(K)</m>.  In other words, the die doesn't remember what it rolls.  We can write this observation in an equation:
<me> E(K) = \frac{1}{6} + \frac{5}{6} (1+E(K)).</me>
The first term of the right side of this equation recognizes that exactly one roll is needed with probability <m>\frac{1}{6}</m>.  We can easily solve this equation for our unknown <m>E(K)=6</m>.</p>
</example>


</subsection>